ABSTRACT (FINAL STABILIZED REVISION)
============================================================

We investigate the hypothesis that mass corresponds to a rate of
irreversible information generation along physical trajectories.

Our working hypothesis is that the proper-time rate of trajectory
surprisal C = -\ln p[\gamma] is proportional to mass-energy:

    M = (ħ / 2π c²) (dC/dτ).

In this framework, mass is interpreted as an information-theoretic rate
rather than a purely geometric or field-theoretic parameter.

We do not modify general relativity or attempt to derive its field
equations. Instead, we examine whether standard vacuum solutions,
including the Schwarzschild and Reissner–Nordström geometries, are
compatible with this interpretation under a small set of
information-theoretic assumptions (causal propagation, holographic
scaling, and the Bekenstein bound).

We find that these solutions exhibit structural consistency with the
proposed framework under spherical symmetry, supporting the plausibility
of the hypothesis without implying that spacetime geometry is uniquely
determined by it.

